Example Angular pattern:

Component calls backend in ngOnInit

Service returns Observable<Item[]>

map operator transforms response

Dropdown shows value and category


Assume backend returns objects like:

[
  { "id": 1, "value": "Apple", "category": "Fruit" },
  { "id": 2, "value": "Carrot", "category": "Vegetable" },
  { "id": 3, "value": "Milk", "category": "Dairy" }
]


---

1. Model (recommended in real projects)

item.model.ts

export interface Item {
  id: number;
  value: string;
  category: string;
}


---

2. Service calling backend

item.service.ts

import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { HttpClient } from '@angular/common/http';
import { Observable, map } from 'rxjs';
import { Item } from './item.model';

@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root'
})
export class ItemService {

  private apiUrl = 'http://localhost:8080/api/items';

  constructor(private http: HttpClient) {}

  getItems(): Observable<Item[]> {
    return this.http.get<Item[]>(this.apiUrl).pipe(
      map(response => {
        return response.map(item => ({
          id: item.id,
          value: item.value,
          category: item.category
        }));
      })
    );
  }
}

map is transforming the backend response before the component receives it.


---

3. Component

dropdown.component.ts

import { Component, OnInit } from '@angular/core';
import { ItemService } from './item.service';
import { Item } from './item.model';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-dropdown',
  templateUrl: './dropdown.component.html'
})
export class DropdownComponent implements OnInit {

  items: Item[] = [];
  selectedItem?: Item;

  constructor(private itemService: ItemService) {}

  ngOnInit(): void {
    this.itemService.getItems().subscribe(data => {
      this.items = data;
    });
  }
}


---

4. HTML Template

dropdown.component.html

<select [(ngModel)]="selectedItem">

  <option *ngFor="let item of items" [ngValue]="item">
    {{item.value}} - {{item.category}}
  </option>

</select>

Displayed dropdown:

Apple - Fruit
Carrot - Vegetable
Milk - Dairy


---

5. More production-grade pattern (better for Angular)

Avoid manual subscription and use async pipe.

Component

items$!: Observable<Item[]>;

ngOnInit(): void {
  this.items$ = this.itemService.getItems();
}

HTML

<select>

  <option *ngFor="let item of items$ | async" [value]="item.id">
    {{item.value}} - {{item.category}}
  </option>

</select>

Benefits:

no manual subscribe

no memory leaks

Angular handles unsubscribe automatically



---

If useful, a more realistic enterprise pattern can also be shown where:

backend response DTO ≠ UI model

map() converts API DTO → UI model

dropdown grouped by category (<optgroup>) for better UX.
